  • Cell turnover rate is increased in psoriasis. (turnover period of 4 - 5 days Vs. 40 - 50 days in normal skin.) Source
  • But proliferation rate is also increased much more -> Overall effect is hyperkeratosis.

  • Parakeratosis - persistence of nuclei in stratum corneum.

    Another classic sign of chronic plaque psoriasis:
    visualization of pinpoint bleeding after removal of scale overlying a psoriatic plaque.
  • improves during pregnancy and worsens post partum (maybe because progesterone in pregnancy downregulates T cell proliferative response). Source
    • Mnemonic: pregnancy - one 1, post partum - 2ps, means worsens psoriasis
    • Mnemonic: LAMBDA - lithium, anti-inflammatory , m-antimalarias, B - beta blockers, D-doxycycline (tetracyclines)
  • Psoriasis is usually non pruritic.
  • Erythrodermic psoriasis is painful.

Subtypes of psoriasis

  • Can be localized palmoplantar pustular psoriasis.
  • (most severe form is Von-Zumbusch - generalized pustular psoriasis)
    • Fever, leukocytosis, hypocalcemia.
    • Possibly complicated by sepsis and renal / hepatic involvement.
  • Pustular psoriasis of pregnancy: usually occurring during T3 of pregnancy.
  • Erythrodermic psoriasis usually occurs in the setting of known worsening or unstable psoriasis.
  • Generalized - Involves most the body surface; erythema and scaling.
  • High risk of complications due to loss of barrier function:
    • Sepsis
    • Electrolyte abnormality
    • Fluid loss
  • Low calcium
  • Withdrawal or excessive use of strong topical corticosteroids
  • Oedema (swelling), particularly of lower legs

Overview of treatment of psoriasis

- **UVB is preferred**.
  • Topical dithranol is an option; it has anti proliferative effects. (inhibits DNA synthesis)
    • Acitretin is not immunosuppressive
  • Tonsillectomy (due to association with strep infection) has been show to improve psoriasis (esp. guttate psoriasis)
  • AKA generalized exfoliative dermatitis.

[!INFO] ⭐Humans are the only host of these.😔

  • ⭐Positive culture is the only confirmatory test of enteric fever.
    • Blood - "early in the disease"; Blood culture is the mainstay of diagnosis of enteric fever. Even so, sensitivity is not 100% (40-80%). Time to positive yield is reduced by centrifugation and culture of the buffy coat because the bacteria live inside the WBCs.
    • Urine and faecies - "first week"Source
    • Bone marrow culture is valuable because it remains positive for upto 5 days after commencement of antibiotic therapy.
    • Of little clinical value because it's positive even with previous infection. Also has low specificity.
    • Checks antibodies to O and H antigens of salmonella. (O antigen - cell wall components, H antigen - the flagellar antigen)
    • However, four fold rise in titre is confirmatory.

#2016GM-OCT/Q10 ⭐

  • Drug resistance is a key issue.
  • Resistance is common to chloramphenicol, amoxicillin, cotrimoxazole. - the older antibiotics used of enteric fever.
    • most strains remain sensitive to Gen 3 cephalosporins and azithyromycin.
  • Some indian studies show increasing resistance to ciprofoloxacin but a recurrence of sensitivity to chloramphenicol , cotrimoxazole and ampicillin.
    • In sri lanka, 2016 guideline suggests ceftriaxone for 10-14 days.
  • Most patients can be managed at home with oral antibiotics. - Harrison's.
  • Response:
    • successful treatment in uncomplicated cases results in clinical improvement in 3-5 days, with fever clearance at 4-6 days.
    • Duration Antibiotics 10 - 14 days (or atleast 5 days after resolution of fever)
    • Relapse can happen 2 to 3 weeks after resolution.
  • Carriers: To be treated with 4 weeks of ciprofloxacin (Harrison's)
  • Single dose IM vaccine with booster in 3 years to be given to food handlers.
    • This is the capsular polysaccharide vaccine.
  • The other vaccine (Ty21a) is live attenuated and given as a capsule.
    • Based on O and H antigens.
  • High risk groups who should get the vaccine:
